---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

export function getStaticPaths() {
  const articles = [
    {
      slug: "dashboard-guven",
      title: "Why Trust Diminishes as Dashboard Numbers Rise",
      desc: "Why does dashboard inflation hurt trust? A practical framework through definition drift, loss of lineage, and maintenance obesity.",
      date: "Feb 1, 2026",
      time: "6 min",
      topics: ["Data Governance", "Dashboard Governance", "Data Lineage", "Semantic Layer"],
      content: `
        <p class="lead">As dashboards multiply, one would expect trust in data to increase. In large enterprises, however, the opposite is often true: as the number of dashboards rises, trust falls.</p>
        <div class="callout"><b>Key Takeaway:</b> Definition drift + loss of lineage + invisible change impact → "Where does this number come from?" remains unanswered → trust erodes.</div>
        
        <h2>The Paradox</h2>
        <p>When the same metric looks different on different screens, the dashboard ceases to be a decision support tool; it begins to produce conflict between teams.</p>
        
        <h2>Three Core Destructions</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><b>Definition Confusion (Metric Drift):</b> The same concept is defined differently by different teams.</li>
          <li><b>Loss of Lineage:</b> When the data journey is invisible, trust is broken.</li>
          <li><b>Maintenance Obesity:</b> A small change can affect hundreds of dashboards, leading to "stale" or incorrect data.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>A Practical Solution Framework</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><b>Official Metric Catalog:</b> Single definition, single dictionary, single ownership.</li>
          <li><b>Lineage Visibility:</b> Traceability from source to report.</li>
          <li><b>Change Discipline:</b> Impact analysis + versioning + clear communication.</li>
          <li><b>Trust Signals:</b> Timestamp of last check, scope, and health status indicators.</li>
        </ul>
      `
    },
    {
      slug: "manuel-kontroller",
      title: "Why Manual Controls Are Still Alive",
      desc: "The real reason behind Excel silos: trust trauma and risk ownership. Trust must be built into the system to reduce manual reconciliation.",
      date: "Feb 1, 2026",
      time: "5 min",
      topics: ["Data Quality", "Reconciliation", "Operational Risk", "Data Lineage"],
      content: `
        <p class="lead">The real reason behind Excel silos is trust trauma and risk ownership. Trust must be built into the automatic system to reduce manual reconciliation.</p>
        <div class="callout"><b>Key Takeaway:</b> Manual controls emerge where the system fails to provide trust. You cannot escape manual work without automating trust.</div>
        <h2>The Problem</h2>
        <p>In a system where constant manual checks are required, trust is placed more on the person checking than on the data itself. This makes scaling impossible.</p>
      `
    },
    {
      slug: "verinin-nabzi",
      title: "Data Autopsy or Data Pulse?",
      desc: "Reports are autopsies; early warning is a data-in-motion discipline. Dynamic thresholds + correlation + action timelines.",
      date: "Feb 1, 2026",
      time: "6 min",
      topics: ["Early Warning", "Data Observability", "Anomaly Detection", "Event Correlation"],
      content: `
        <p class="lead">Reports are autopsies; early warning is a data-in-motion discipline. Dynamic thresholds + correlation + action timelines.</p>
        <div class="callout"><b>Key Takeaway:</b> Instead of performing an autopsy on data, keep your finger on its pulse. Take action before problems arise with early warning systems.</div>
      `
    },
    {
      slug: "is-analizi",
      title: "Business Analysis: Where Everything Starts and Ends",
      desc: "Success starts before the code. A professional approach to clarifying scope and reducing regression risk with 5W1H + impact analysis.",
      date: "Feb 1, 2026",
      time: "7 min",
      topics: ["Business Analysis", "Scope Management", "Impact Analysis", "CR Process"],
      content: `
        <p class="lead">The fate of a project is often determined before the first line of code. Business analysis filters requests through business value, feasibility, and system integrity.</p>
        <div class="callout"><b>Key Takeaway:</b> Break the "simple report" myth. Clarify scope and manage regression risk with 5W1H + impact analysis.</div>
        
        <h2>Definition Chaos</h2>
        <p>If the same concept is given different meanings, development produces risk rather than speed.</p>
        
        <h2>Methodology</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><b>5W1H:</b> What, why, how, where, when, who.</li>
          <li><b>Impact Analysis:</b> Make the domino effect visible.</li>
          <li><b>CR Discipline:</b> Manage changes with precision.</li>
        </ul>
      `
    },
    {
      slug: "rag-ne-zaman-ise-yarar",
      title: "When Does RAG (Retrieval) Work and When Does It Mislead?",
      desc: "The success of RAG depends more on the quality of information access than the model: chunking, metadata, relevance, freshness, and attribution.",
      date: "Feb 1, 2026",
      time: "8 min",
      topics: ["RAG", "GenAI", "Information Retrieval", "Document AI"],
      content: `
        <p class="lead">RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) seems like the most practical way to speak your <b>enterprise's knowledge</b> rather than just "what the model knows."</p>
        <div class="callout"><b>Key Takeaway:</b> RAG works if <b>chunking + metadata + relevance + freshness + attribution</b> are established correctly.</div>
        
        <h2>When Does RAG Really Work?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><b>When your knowledge is scattered across documents but repeatable:</b> Procedures, contract clauses, runbooks.</li>
          <li><b>When the "answer = source quote + brief comment" format is suitable.</b></li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>When Does RAG Mislead?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><b>When the source is ambiguous or contradictory:</b> The model experiences confusion.</li>
          <li><b>When Freshness is not managed correctly.</b></li>
        </ul>
      `
    },
    {
      slug: "genai-guven-standardi",
      title: "How to Establish a 'Trust Standard' in Enterprise GenAI?",
      desc: "Trust in GenAI is built through processes, measurement, and governance. Leveraging attribution, access, evaluation, and traceability.",
      date: "Feb 1, 2026",
      time: "9 min",
      topics: ["GenAI", "Governance", "Security", "LLM Evaluation"],
      content: `
        <p class="lead">In Enterprise GenAI, the real question isn't "how smart is the model?" but <b>"how much can I trust the output?"</b></p>
        <div class="callout"><b>Key Takeaway:</b> A trust standard is established through <b>attribution</b>, <b>access (RBAC)</b>, <b>evaluation</b>, and <b>observability</b>.</div>
        
        <h2>7 Components of the Trust Standard</h2>
        <h3>1) Data Boundaries and Content Life Cycle</h3>
        <p>What content is the "single source of truth"? A document life cycle must be defined.</p>
        
        <h3>2) Access / RBAC</h3>
        <p>Access control is not left to the model; it is managed by the system.</p>
        
        <h3>3) Attribution (Evidence-First)</h3>
        <p>The "Answer + Evidence" structure increases trust multiplier effect.</p>
      `
    }
  ];

  return articles.map(article => ({
    params: { slug: article.slug },
    props: { article, articles }
  }));
}

const { article, articles } = Astro.props;
const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: "Insights", url: "/insights" },
  { name: article.title, url: `/insights/${article.slug}` }
];

const relatedArticles = articles.filter(a => a.slug !== article.slug).slice(0, 3);
---

<Layout title={`${article.title} | Intellica Insights`} description={article.desc} breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}>
  <section class="section section--white">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="article-layout">
        
        <!-- Main Content -->
        <article class="article-main anim-fade-up">
          <div class="insight-meta">
            <span>{article.date}</span>
            <span class="dot"></span>
            <span>{article.time} read</span>
          </div>
          <h1>{article.title}</h1>
          <div class="insight-tags" style="margin-bottom: 40px;">
            {article.topics.map(t => <span class="topic-pill">{t}</span>)}
          </div>
          
          <div class="article-body" set:html={article.content} />
          
          <div class="article-footer" style="margin-top: 64px; padding-top: 32px; border-top: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">
            <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center;">
              <a href="/insights" class="btn btn-ghost btn-pill">← Back to All Insights</a>
              <div class="share-links">
                <!-- Placeholder for share -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
        
        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <aside class="article-sidebar anim-fade-up">
          <div class="sidebar-block card-light">
            <h3>Related Insights</h3>
            <div class="related-list">
              {relatedArticles.map(ra => (
                <a href={`/insights/${ra.slug}`} class="related-item">
                  <h4>{ra.title}</h4>
                  <p>{ra.desc.substring(0, 80)}...</p>
                </a>
              ))}
            </div>
            <a href="/insights" class="btn btn-primary btn-pill btn-full" style="margin-top: 24px;">Explore Library</a>
          </div>
          
          <div class="sidebar-block card-light" style="margin-top: 32px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(16,185,129,0.05), rgba(59,130,246,0.05));">
            <h3>Adapting this insight</h3>
            <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--clr-light-muted); margin-bottom: 20px;">
              Want to apply this methodology to your organization? Let's discuss your specific challenges.
            </p>
            <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary btn-pill btn-full">Contact Expert</a>
          </div>
        </aside>
        
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
.article-layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 340px;
  gap: 64px;
  align-items: start;
}
.article-main h1 {
  font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3.5rem);
  line-height: 1.1;
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
  margin-bottom: 24px;
}
.insight-meta {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 10px;
  font-size: 0.8rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--clr-primary);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
}
.insight-meta .dot {
  width: 4px; height: 4px; border-radius: 50%; background: #cbd5e1;
}
.insight-tags {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 8px;
}
.topic-pill {
  font-size: 0.75rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  padding: 6px 14px;
  border-radius: 100px;
  background: #f1f5f9;
  color: #475569;
}

/* Article Styles */
.article-body :global(.lead) {
  font-size: 1.25rem;
  line-height: 1.8;
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
  margin-bottom: 32px;
}
.article-body :global(.callout) {
  padding: 24px 32px;
  background: #f8fafc;
  border-left: 4px solid var(--clr-primary);
  border-radius: 0 16px 16px 0;
  margin-bottom: 40px;
  font-style: italic;
  color: #334155;
}
.article-body :global(h2) {
  font-size: 1.8rem;
  margin-top: 48px;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
}
.article-body :global(h3) {
  font-size: 1.4rem;
  margin-top: 32px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
}
.article-body :global(p) {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: var(--clr-light-muted);
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}
.article-body :global(ul) {
  margin-bottom: 32px;
  padding-left: 20px;
}
.article-body :global(li) {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  color: var(--clr-light-muted);
  margin-bottom: 12px;
  list-style-type: disc;
}
.article-body :global(b), .article-body :global(strong) {
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
  font-weight: 700;
}

/* Sidebar */
.sidebar-block {
  padding: 32px;
  border-radius: 24px;
}
.sidebar-block h3 {
  font-size: 1.2rem;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
}
.related-list {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 24px;
}
.related-item {
  text-decoration: none;
  display: block;
}
.related-item h4 {
  font-size: 1rem;
  color: var(--clr-light-text);
  margin-bottom: 8px;
  line-height: 1.4;
  transition: color 0.2s ease;
}
.related-item:hover h4 { color: var(--clr-primary); }
.related-item p {
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  color: var(--clr-light-muted);
  line-height: 1.5;
}
.article-sidebar .btn-full { width: 100%; text-align: center; justify-content: center; }

@media (max-width: 1024px) {
  .article-layout { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 48px; }
  .article-sidebar { order: -1; }
}
</style>
